{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017SgVezRZiLun69f55gKxVL","type":"tool_result","content":"85:ther propose a Matryoshka-style sparse activation\n93:across LIBERO-Plus and RoboTwin, as well as\n201:benefits from leveraging teacher signals across depths (Sun\n225:the shared projector, ROCKET introduces a Matryoshka-\n240:avoid gradient conflicts and a Matryoshka-style sparse ac-\n270:dation models such asVGGT(Wang et al., 2025a),Depth\n276:to transfer spatial knowledge from pretrained teachers to\n278:token features from one layer to a fixed teacher layer.\n281:to VGGT features;REPA(Yu et al., 2024) alignsshallow\n285:VGGT. Although effective, these methods typically super-\n294:SF OpenVLA –24 / 32VGGT – 24 / 24\n296:3DRS LLaV A –32 / 32VGGT – 24 / 24\n393:3D vision foundation model as teacher.We assume\n395:theteacher, which provides geometry-groundedpatch to-\n396:kenrepresentations. Such models (e.g., VGGT (Wang\n404:student model by matching them to a teacher’s interme-\n411:τ ∈R dT denote the student/teacher\n412:vision representations at student layer s and teacher layer τ.\n413:SF aligns one student layer s⋆ to one teacher layer τ ⋆ (i.e.,\n445:i=1 (teacher), previous multi-layer\n466:be cone-to-cone, yet learned projectors decouple.To\n468:student and teacher backbones as residual dynamical sys-\n475:tent with the “cone effect” (Gao et al., 2019). This suggests\n476:multi-layer alignment should learn a consistentcone-to-cone\n477:mapping from the student residual stream to the teacher\n573:Proposition: Jacobian-induced gradient interference\n589:on teacher-side error signals:\n734:(iii) Matryoshka-style Activation\n747:use the outputs from VGGT layers {1,3,9,15,21} to directly predict the depth map, demonstrating that different layers contain rich 3D\n756:(iii) Matryoshka-style activation for balancing depths.\n762:the shared projector, ROCKET introduces a Matryoshka-\n777:teacher mapping that is consistent across depth.