{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FDS7cF3yqkUnukaQV4nVkH","type":"tool_result","content":"Figure 3.Performance on LIBERO across differ-\nent training stages. See Table 9 for details.\nHierarchical information\nCommon mappings are \nachieved via a shared projector Independent projectors \nlearn distinct paths\nFigure 4.A cone-effect perspective on alignment.\nTable 2.Comparisons with SOTA VLA models on the LIBERO benchmark.\nMethod Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\nBasic 2D VLA\nOcto (Ghosh et al., 2024) 78.9 85.7 84.6 51.1 75.1\nOpenVLA (Kim et al., 2024) 84.7 88.4 79.2 53.7 76.5\nWorldVLA (Cen et al., 2025) 87.6 96.2 83.4 60.0 81.8\nDita (Hou et al., 2025) 84.2 96.3 85.4 63.8 82.4\nPI0 (Black et al., 2024) 96.8 98.8 95.8 85.2 94.2\nInternVLA (Chen et al., 2025b) 98.0 99.0 93.8 92.6 95.9\nGR00T N1.6 (Bjorck et al., 2025) 97.7 98.5 97.5 94.3 97.0\nVOTE (Lin et al., 2025b) 98.8 99.8 97.6 95.6 98.0\nTraceVLA (Zheng et al., 2024) 84.6 85.2 75.1 54.1 74.8\nThinkAct (Huang et al., 2025a) 88.3 91.4 87.1 70.9 84.4\nUniVLA (Bu et al., 2025) 96.5 96.8 95.6 92.0 95.2\nMemoryVLA (Shi et al., 2025) 98.4 98.4 96.4 93.4 96.5\nCronusVLA (Shi et al., 2025) 97.3 99.6 96.9 94.0 97.0\nOpenVLA-OFT (Kim et al., 2025) 97.6 98.4 97.9 94.5 97.1\n3D VLA with explicit 3D inputs\nSpatialVLA (Qu et al., 2025) 88.2 89.9 78.6 55.5 78.1\nGeoVLA (Sun et al., 2025) 98.4 99.0 96.6 96.6 97.7\n3D-CA VLA (Bhat et al., 2025) 98.2 99.8 98.2 96.1 98.1\n3D VLA with representation alignment\nGLaD (Guo et al., 2025) 95.0 97.4 94.4 89.4 94.1\nSpatial Forcing (Li et al., 2025) 99.4 99.6 98.8 96.0 98.5\nROCKET(Ours) 98.2 99.8 98.8 97.0 98.5\n{p(i)\nΦ }N\ni=1 that share parameters, but expose increasing ef-\nfective capacity for deeper layers.\nTraining objective.Our final training objective combines\nthe task loss for action prediction with the proposed multi-\nlayer alignment regularizer:\nLROCKET =L action +λ 1\nN\nNX\ni=1\nℓ\n\u0010\np(i)\nΦ\n\u0000\nhS\nsi\n\u0001\n, h T\nτi\n\u0011\n,(16)\nwhere Laction is defined in Eq. (2), and λ balances task\nlearning and representation alignment. By default, we use\nℓ(a, b) = 1−cos(a, b)and setλ= 0.5.\n5. Main Result\n5.1. Experimental Setup\nLIBERO and LIBERO-Plus.We conduct experiments\non LIBERO (Liu et al., 2023) and LIBERO-PLUS(Fei\net al., 2025). Each benchmark comprises four sub-datasets\n(task suites). Following the official protocol of LIBERO-\nPLUSas well as the common practice used in PI0/PI0.5, we\nmix the four sub-datasets during training and evaluate asin-\nglemodel on the four corresponding test suites. Unless oth-\nerwise specified, we fine-tune the OPENVLA-7B pretrained\nweights on LIBERO and LIBERO-PLUS. We adopt the\ntraining setting of SF and OPENVLA-OFT. Specifically,\nTable 3.Success rate (%) of the PI0.5 with different representation\nalignment strategies on the LIBERO.\nMethod Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\nBaseline 96.4 98.2 95.0 82.2 93.0\nSpatial Forcing 97.8 97.8 94.4 85.8 94.0\nROCKET 96.4 98.8 96.6 89.2 95.3\nwe perform LoRA fine-tuning for 50,000 steps with batch\nsize 32. In addition, to compare multiple methods under the\nfull fine-tuningregime as in PI0.5, we run full fine-tuning\non LIBERO for30,000steps with batch size64.\nRoboTwin 2.0.We follow the official training protocol","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c125573-d846-41a4-a04d-12d87f79bf20","uuid":"c5515401-d7be-4551-98ac-c75ec9c7d498","timestamp":"2026-04-27T15:01:54.829Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"Figure 3.Performance on LIBERO across differ-\nent training stages. See Table 9 for details.\nHierarchical information\nCommon mappings are \nachieved via a shared projector Independent projectors \nlearn distinct paths\nFigure 4.A cone-effect perspective on alignment.\nTable 2.Comparisons with SOTA VLA models on the LIBERO benchmark.\nMethod Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\nBasic 2D VLA\nOcto (Ghosh et al., 2024) 78.9 85.7 84.6 51.1 75.1\nOpenVLA (Kim et al., 2024) 84.7 88.4 79.2 53.7 76.5\nWorldVLA (Cen et al., 2025) 87.6 96.2 83.4 60.0 81.8\nDita (Hou et al., 2025) 84.2 96.3 85.4 63.8 82.4\nPI0 (Black et al., 2024) 96.8 98.8 95.8 85.2 94.2\nInternVLA (Chen et al., 2025b) 98.0 99.0 93.8 92.6 95.9\nGR00T N1.6 (Bjorck et al., 2025) 97.7 98.5 97.5 94.3 97.0\nVOTE (Lin et al., 2025b) 98.8 99.8 97.6 95.6 98.0\nTraceVLA (Zheng et al., 2024) 84.6 85.2 75.1 54.1 74.8\nThinkAct (Huang et al., 2025a) 88.3 91.4 87.1 70.9 84.4\nUniVLA (Bu et al., 2025) 96.5 96.8 95.6 92.0 95.2\nMemoryVLA (Shi et al., 2025) 98.4 98.4 96.4 93.4 96.5\nCronusVLA (Shi et al., 2025) 97.3 99.6 96.9 94.0 97.0\nOpenVLA-OFT (Kim et al., 2025) 97.6 98.4 97.9 94.5 97.1\n3D VLA with explicit 3D inputs\nSpatialVLA (Qu et al., 2025) 88.2 89.9 78.6 55.5 78.1\nGeoVLA (Sun et al., 2025) 98.4 99.0 96.6 96.6 97.7\n3D-CA VLA (Bhat et al., 2025) 98.2 99.8 98.2 96.1 98.1\n3D VLA with representation alignment\nGLaD (Guo et al., 2025) 95.0 97.4 94.4 89.4 94.1\nSpatial Forcing (Li et al., 2025) 99.4 99.6 98.8 96.0 98.5\nROCKET(Ours) 98.2 99.8 98.8 97.0 98.5\n{p(i)\nΦ }N\ni=1 that share parameters, but expose increasing ef-\nfective capacity for deeper layers.\nTraining objective.Our final training objective combines\nthe task loss for action prediction with the proposed multi-\nlayer alignment regularizer:\nLROCKET =L action +λ 1\nN\nNX\ni=1\nℓ\n\u0010\np(i)\nΦ\n\u0000\nhS\nsi\n\u0001\n, h T\nτi\n\u0011\n,(16)\nwhere Laction is defined in Eq. (2), and λ balances task\nlearning and representation alignment. By default, we use\nℓ(a, b) = 1−cos(a, b)and setλ= 0.5.\n5. Main Result\n5.1. Experimental Setup\nLIBERO and LIBERO-Plus.We conduct experiments\non LIBERO (Liu et al., 2023) and LIBERO-PLUS(Fei\net al., 2025). Each benchmark comprises four sub-datasets\n(task suites). Following the official protocol of LIBERO-\nPLUSas well as the common practice used in PI0/PI0.5, we\nmix the four sub-datasets during training and evaluate asin-\nglemodel on the four corresponding test suites. Unless oth-\nerwise specified, we fine-tune the OPENVLA-7B pretrained\nweights on LIBERO and LIBERO-PLUS. We adopt the\ntraining setting of SF and OPENVLA-OFT. Specifically,\nTable 3.Success rate (%) of the PI0.5 with different representation\nalignment strategies on the LIBERO.\nMethod Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\nBaseline 96.4 98.2 95.0 82.2 93.0\nSpatial Forcing 97.8 97.8 94.4 85.8 94.0\nROCKET 96.4 98.8 96.6 89.2 95.3\nwe perform LoRA fine-tuning for 50,000 steps with batch\nsize 32. In addition, to compare multiple methods under the\nfull fine-tuningregime as in PI0.5, we run full fine-tuning\non LIBERO for30,000steps with batch size64.\nRoboTwin 2.0.We follow the official training protocol","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
