{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01ADX31Ad4FqyqJjiNhPy3QX","type":"tool_result","content":"ROCKET: Residual-Oriented Multi-Layer Alignment for Spatially-Aware Vision-Language-Action Models\nMove\nPlayingcard Turn Switch\nOpen\nMicrowave Beat Block Place Shoes AVG.\n1\nFigure 6.Success rate (%) on RoboTwin 2.0 (ALOHA) under Easy and Hard settings across five bimanual tasks, comparing ROCKET\nwith DP (Chi et al., 2025), RDT (Liu et al., 2024), and PI0 (Black et al., 2024).\nResults in Table 5 show that even without expensive post-\nhoc search, most reasonable selection strategies provide\nconsistent gains, suggesting that ROCKET is robust to layer\nchoice. Unless otherwise stated, we adopt the E2M-Last1\nstrategy as the default setting. Implementation details and\nthe exact layer indices are provided in Appendix I.1, I.2.\nTable 5.Comparison of layer selection strategies on LIBERO.\nStrategy Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\nBaseline 97.2 98.4 95.6 88.6 95.0\nUniform-8 98.2 99.8 96.4 95.0 97.4\nE2M-Last1 96.2 98.0 97.2 93.6 96.3\nShallow 97.8 99.8 95.4 85.6 94.7\nMiddle 89.4 99.8 94.2 91.2 93.7\nDeep 92.0 99.8 95.6 93.6 95.3\nSim-1-Top 92.8 99.8 95.0 86.8 93.6\nSim-1-Last 93.8 100.0 95.6 92.8 95.6\nSim-2-Top 91.6 100.0 96.0 94.0 95.4\nSim-2-Last 91.8 100.0 93.6 94.8 95.1\n6.3. Data and Computational Efficiency\nWe evaluate the efficiency ofROCKET from three perspec-\ntives:(i) Limited-data training.Using 1%, 5%, and 10%\nrandom subsets of LIBERO (each trained for 30k steps),\nTable 6 shows that ROCKET still achieves strong perfor-\nmance, indicating high data efficiency, which is particularly\nimportant in robotics where data collection is costly.(ii)\nConvergence speed.In Fig. 3, ROCKET outperforms the\nbaseline by ∼10% at around 10k steps and continues to\nimprove thereafter, suggesting that the proposed multi-level\nalignment mechanism more effectively exploits spatial cues\nacross different layers. Please refer to Table 9 for the com-\nplete results.(iii) Computational cost to reach SOTA.\nTable 7 summarizes the compute overhead of same-sized\nmodels reported in Table 2. ROCKET reaches SOTA perfor-\nmance while the previous best method incurs 24× higher\ncost, demonstrating strong overall computational efficiency\namong post-training methods.\n6.4. Ablation Study\nWe ablate the key components of ROCKET. Introducing\nmulti-layer alignment withindependentprojectors degrades\nperformance to 80.0%, indicating gradient interference\nacross layers. Replacing independent projectors with the\nTable 6.Limited-data training on LIBERO, SR(%).\nRatio Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\n1% 75.0 88.8 65.0 65.6 73.6\n5% 94.2 95.0 75.2 69.0 83.4\n10% 94.0 91.8 78.6 72.6 84.3\n100% 96.2 98.0 97.2 93.6 96.3\nTable 7.Training cost comparison of same-size models on\nLIBERO.Costis estimated as#Model×BatchSize×Steps.\nMethod Avg. Cost Details\nThinkAct 84.4 6.0× 1×128×75k\nUniVLA 95.2 0.96× 1×192×8k\nOpenVLA-OFT 97.1 25.6× 4×64×150k\nGeoVLA 97.7 3.2× 1×256×20k\n3D-CA VLA 98.1 3.0× 4×8×150k\nSpatial Forcing 98.5 24.0× 4×64×150k\nROCKET 98.5 1.0× 1×32×50k\nproposedsharedprojector improves performance to 98.2%.\nFinally, adding the Matryoshka-style sparse activation fur-\nther increases performance to98.5%.\nTable 8.Ablation study ofROCKETon LIBERO.\nMethod Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\nBaseline 96.9 98.7 97.6 94.8 96.4\n+ Multi-layer 93.6 99.2 42.2 85.0 80.0\n+ Shared 99.0 99.8 97.0 96.8 98.2\n+ Matryoshka 98.2 99.8 98.8 97.0 98.5\n7. Conclusion\nWe presented ROCKET, a residual-oriented multi-layer rep-\nresentation alignment framework that transfers 3D spatial\npriors from a strong vision foundation model into 2D-\npretrained VLA models. By using alayer-invariant shared\nprojector, ROCKET mitigates gradient interference that\narises in na¨ıve multi-layer distillation, and our Matryoshka-\nstyle sparse activation further balances supervision across\ndepths. Extensive experiments show that ROCKET consis-\ntently improves spatial grounding and generalization across\ndatasets and VLA backbones, achieving near state-of-the-art\nperformance on LIBERO with only a small fraction of the\ncompute. We hope ROCKET offers a simple and scalable\nroute to more reliable 3D-aware robotic manipulation.\n8\n=== PAGE 9 ===\n440","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c125573-d846-41a4-a04d-12d87f79bf20","uuid":"0a2573f7-f73c-4f21-a6bf-b0978c6a0ee0","timestamp":"2026-04-27T15:02:00.597Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"ROCKET: Residual-Oriented Multi-Layer Alignment for Spatially-Aware Vision-Language-Action Models\nMove\nPlayingcard Turn Switch\nOpen\nMicrowave Beat Block Place Shoes AVG.\n1\nFigure 6.Success rate (%) on RoboTwin 2.0 (ALOHA) under Easy and Hard settings across five bimanual tasks, comparing ROCKET\nwith DP (Chi et al., 2025), RDT (Liu et al., 2024), and PI0 (Black et al., 2024).\nResults in Table 5 show that even without expensive post-\nhoc search, most reasonable selection strategies provide\nconsistent gains, suggesting that ROCKET is robust to layer\nchoice. Unless otherwise stated, we adopt the E2M-Last1\nstrategy as the default setting. Implementation details and\nthe exact layer indices are provided in Appendix I.1, I.2.\nTable 5.Comparison of layer selection strategies on LIBERO.\nStrategy Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\nBaseline 97.2 98.4 95.6 88.6 95.0\nUniform-8 98.2 99.8 96.4 95.0 97.4\nE2M-Last1 96.2 98.0 97.2 93.6 96.3\nShallow 97.8 99.8 95.4 85.6 94.7\nMiddle 89.4 99.8 94.2 91.2 93.7\nDeep 92.0 99.8 95.6 93.6 95.3\nSim-1-Top 92.8 99.8 95.0 86.8 93.6\nSim-1-Last 93.8 100.0 95.6 92.8 95.6\nSim-2-Top 91.6 100.0 96.0 94.0 95.4\nSim-2-Last 91.8 100.0 93.6 94.8 95.1\n6.3. Data and Computational Efficiency\nWe evaluate the efficiency ofROCKET from three perspec-\ntives:(i) Limited-data training.Using 1%, 5%, and 10%\nrandom subsets of LIBERO (each trained for 30k steps),\nTable 6 shows that ROCKET still achieves strong perfor-\nmance, indicating high data efficiency, which is particularly\nimportant in robotics where data collection is costly.(ii)\nConvergence speed.In Fig. 3, ROCKET outperforms the\nbaseline by ∼10% at around 10k steps and continues to\nimprove thereafter, suggesting that the proposed multi-level\nalignment mechanism more effectively exploits spatial cues\nacross different layers. Please refer to Table 9 for the com-\nplete results.(iii) Computational cost to reach SOTA.\nTable 7 summarizes the compute overhead of same-sized\nmodels reported in Table 2. ROCKET reaches SOTA perfor-\nmance while the previous best method incurs 24× higher\ncost, demonstrating strong overall computational efficiency\namong post-training methods.\n6.4. Ablation Study\nWe ablate the key components of ROCKET. Introducing\nmulti-layer alignment withindependentprojectors degrades\nperformance to 80.0%, indicating gradient interference\nacross layers. Replacing independent projectors with the\nTable 6.Limited-data training on LIBERO, SR(%).\nRatio Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\n1% 75.0 88.8 65.0 65.6 73.6\n5% 94.2 95.0 75.2 69.0 83.4\n10% 94.0 91.8 78.6 72.6 84.3\n100% 96.2 98.0 97.2 93.6 96.3\nTable 7.Training cost comparison of same-size models on\nLIBERO.Costis estimated as#Model×BatchSize×Steps.\nMethod Avg. Cost Details\nThinkAct 84.4 6.0× 1×128×75k\nUniVLA 95.2 0.96× 1×192×8k\nOpenVLA-OFT 97.1 25.6× 4×64×150k\nGeoVLA 97.7 3.2× 1×256×20k\n3D-CA VLA 98.1 3.0× 4×8×150k\nSpatial Forcing 98.5 24.0× 4×64×150k\nROCKET 98.5 1.0× 1×32×50k\nproposedsharedprojector improves performance to 98.2%.\nFinally, adding the Matryoshka-style sparse activation fur-\nther increases performance to98.5%.\nTable 8.Ablation study ofROCKETon LIBERO.\nMethod Spatial Object Goal Long Avg.\nBaseline 96.9 98.7 97.6 94.8 96.4\n+ Multi-layer 93.6 99.2 42.2 85.0 80.0\n+ Shared 99.0 99.8 97.0 96.8 98.2\n+ Matryoshka 98.2 99.8 98.8 97.0 98.5\n7. Conclusion\nWe presented ROCKET, a residual-oriented multi-layer rep-\nresentation alignment framework that transfers 3D spatial\npriors from a strong vision foundation model into 2D-\npretrained VLA models. By using alayer-invariant shared\nprojector, ROCKET mitigates gradient interference that\narises in na¨ıve multi-layer distillation, and our Matryoshka-\nstyle sparse activation further balances supervision across\ndepths. Extensive experiments show that ROCKET consis-\ntently improves spatial grounding and generalization across\ndatasets and VLA backbones, achieving near state-of-the-art\nperformance on LIBERO with only a small fraction of the\ncompute. We hope ROCKET offers a simple and scalable\nroute to more reliable 3D-aware robotic manipulation.\n8\n=== PAGE 9 ===\n440","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
