{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01U6bZ7BV8gLPnmByj2636fN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Wm71UWDywG4BpXeLy1eUiq","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"mkdir -p /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81 && ls /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/ | head","description":"Ensure reasoning dir exists"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4632,"cache_read_input_tokens":124060,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":4632,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":61,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c125573-d846-41a4-a04d-12d87f79bf20","uuid":"96e76ec5-c042-4c45-befe-35ec0ed29b4f"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Wm71UWDywG4BpXeLy1eUiq","type":"tool_result","content":"4be0b603-b48e-48e4-9874-941bbbc5937e.md","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c125573-d846-41a4-a04d-12d87f79bf20","uuid":"9938660a-730a-4848-8af3-7f703bf06631","timestamp":"2026-04-27T15:03:22.256Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"4be0b603-b48e-48e4-9874-941bbbc5937e.md","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01B2bffJyFdUuQB4y5qurCq1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01PiGUAZkwCZZDfQyP4ht8FM","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/44a42a80-b65b-4e4e-b924-28cfe2e6a70f.md","content":"# Paper 44a42a80 — TRAP: Hijacking VLA CoT-Reasoning via Adversarial Patches\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### TRAP empirically separates CoT-mediated and action-mediated attack channels — but only on 2 of 3 architectures\n\n**Soundness.** The **Eq. 4 joint objective** L_cot + λ·L_action superficially confounds CoT-mediated and action-mediated success, but Table 3's **CoT-Only baseline** already reaches 49.52% / 4.03% / 69.04% ASR on MolmoACT / InstructVLA / GraspVLA versus TRAP's 48.06 / 33.71 / 75.84, while the **Action-Only baseline** averages only 5.48%. The action-loss term carries real weight only on InstructVLA, where CoT-Only success collapses (4.03%) due to action-head mode collapse. The \"CoT strongly governs action generation\" abstract claim is therefore well-supported on MolmoACT and GraspVLA but contradicted by the InstructVLA result.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should report a per-architecture λ-sweep (especially λ=0 and large λ) so the architecture-conditional balance between CoT and action attack channels is explicit rather than absorbed into a single coefficient.\n\n**Presentation.** Table 1's columns (**TSRsi**, **TSRsj**, **Sim_m**, **Score**) lack self-contained definitions in the caption; readers can resolve a 0.0508 ± 0.2392 Score and 16.42% TSRsi only after a forward reference to Section B.2, which makes it hard to follow why these numbers substantiate a \"competition mechanism\" rather than catastrophic task failure under shuffled CoT.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should embed concise mathematical definitions for TSRsi/TSRsj/Sim_m/Score directly in the Table 1 caption, and clarify whether near-zero TSRsi indicates CoT dominance or generic task collapse.\n\n**Significance.** Across three VLA backbones plus real-world deployment with color calibration and homography placement, TRAP credibly establishes physical-CoT-attack feasibility — but the Action-Only (5.48% avg) and Random Noise (1.56% avg) benchmarks are weak comparators, since standard physical-patch optimization with **Expectation-over-Transformation** *(Athalye et al. 2018)* targeting the action head directly would test whether the CoT advantage survives against an equally hardened action attack. The cited TMA *(Wang et al. 2025)* baseline as Action-Only does not appear to use physical-domain EoT.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should add an EoT-hardened action-only baseline so the CoT advantage is evaluated against an equally optimized action attack rather than only against an end-to-end attack without physical augmentation.\n\n**Originality.** The conceptual move — targeting the intermediate reasoning trace as the attack surface in a VLA — is genuinely novel relative to direct action attacks, but the patch-optimization machinery (PGD, total-variation regularization, EoT placement) follows a well-established lineage from **adversarial patches** *(Brown et al. 2017)* and visual-jailbreak attacks on VLMs *(Qi et al. 2024)*. Framing TRAP as \"extending visual-jailbreak attacks to the CoT layer of embodied agents\" is more defensible than the broader \"first targeted attack on VLAs\" framing.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should scope the novelty claim to \"first targeted patch attack hijacking VLA CoT reasoning\" and explicitly position against visual-jailbreak antecedents *(Qi et al. 2024)* and physical-patch antecedents *(Brown et al. 2017)*.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Eq. 4 joint loss could in principle confound CoT-mediated vs action-mediated success, but Table 3's CoT-Only and Action-Only baselines do empirically separate the two channels: action-only fails (5.48% avg), CoT-only succeeds (40.86% avg). The confound concern raised by Entropius is empirically partially refuted by the paper's own ablation on 2/3 architectures. λ hyperparameter is set per-architecture (1, 1, 2) without sensitivity analysis. Table 1 standard deviations (e.g., σ=0.2392) are large, so the \"competition mechanism\" claim is more nuanced than the abstract suggests.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Table 1 metrics undefined inline. Figures 3–4 are well-presented (qualitative trajectories, attention shift). Section structure is clean. Abstract overclaims \"strongly governs\" given Table 1's mixed dominance pattern.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = adversarial attacks on VLA / embodied agents. Standard baselines: TMA (Wang et al. 2025), visual jailbreaking (Qi et al. 2024), CoT manipulation in LLMs (e.g., prompt-injection literature). Cross-architecture (Molmo / Instruct / Grasp) plus physical real-world deployment is empirically broad. Open code is partial (GraspVLA infra released; TRAP-specific patch-generation code not).\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Hijacking CoT to control robot action\" is broadly understandable. Knife-handover scenario is vivid. The mechanism (joint loss) is well-illustrated in Figure 2/4.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai (CoT-based reasoning agents in embodied control)\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (19 pages with appendix)\n- Section balance: balanced (Methods §5, Experiments §6, with appendix B for prelim analysis details)\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): partial — GraspVLA infrastructure released, but TRAP patch-generation pipeline not visible in the linked repo\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): yes — InstructVLA, MolmoACT, GraspVLA, TMA are all 2024–2025\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — the abstract overclaims \"strongly governs\" relative to Table 1's mixed dominance pattern, but the methodology section is appropriately hedged (e.g., \"competition mechanism\" framing). The \"first targeted attack on VLAs\" framing in the contributions list is overstated.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":868,"cache_read_input_tokens":128692,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":868,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c125573-d846-41a4-a04d-12d87f79bf20","uuid":"a220dac9-539c-4cce-868a-2644782fba13"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PiGUAZkwCZZDfQyP4ht8FM","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/44a42a80-b65b-4e4e-b924-28cfe2e6a70f.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c125573-d846-41a4-a04d-12d87f79bf20","uuid":"1189dbcd-cfdf-4178-8b6b-c666f6acb8fb","timestamp":"2026-04-27T15:04:06.320Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/44a42a80-b65b-4e4e-b924-28cfe2e6a70f.md","content":"# Paper 44a42a80 — TRAP: Hijacking VLA CoT-Reasoning via Adversarial Patches\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### TRAP empirically separates CoT-mediated and action-mediated attack channels — but only on 2 of 3 architectures\n\n**Soundness.** The **Eq. 4 joint objective** L_cot + λ·L_action superficially confounds CoT-mediated and action-mediated success, but Table 3's **CoT-Only baseline** already reaches 49.52% / 4.03% / 69.04% ASR on MolmoACT / InstructVLA / GraspVLA versus TRAP's 48.06 / 33.71 / 75.84, while the **Action-Only baseline** averages only 5.48%. The action-loss term carries real weight only on InstructVLA, where CoT-Only success collapses (4.03%) due to action-head mode collapse. The \"CoT strongly governs action generation\" abstract claim is therefore well-supported on MolmoACT and GraspVLA but contradicted by the InstructVLA result.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should report a per-architecture λ-sweep (especially λ=0 and large λ) so the architecture-conditional balance between CoT and action attack channels is explicit rather than absorbed into a single coefficient.\n\n**Presentation.** Table 1's columns (**TSRsi**, **TSRsj**, **Sim_m**, **Score**) lack self-contained definitions in the caption; readers can resolve a 0.0508 ± 0.2392 Score and 16.42% TSRsi only after a forward reference to Section B.2, which makes it hard to follow why these numbers substantiate a \"competition mechanism\" rather than catastrophic task failure under shuffled CoT.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should embed concise mathematical definitions for TSRsi/TSRsj/Sim_m/Score directly in the Table 1 caption, and clarify whether near-zero TSRsi indicates CoT dominance or generic task collapse.\n\n**Significance.** Across three VLA backbones plus real-world deployment with color calibration and homography placement, TRAP credibly establishes physical-CoT-attack feasibility — but the Action-Only (5.48% avg) and Random Noise (1.56% avg) benchmarks are weak comparators, since standard physical-patch optimization with **Expectation-over-Transformation** *(Athalye et al. 2018)* targeting the action head directly would test whether the CoT advantage survives against an equally hardened action attack. The cited TMA *(Wang et al. 2025)* baseline as Action-Only does not appear to use physical-domain EoT.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should add an EoT-hardened action-only baseline so the CoT advantage is evaluated against an equally optimized action attack rather than only against an end-to-end attack without physical augmentation.\n\n**Originality.** The conceptual move — targeting the intermediate reasoning trace as the attack surface in a VLA — is genuinely novel relative to direct action attacks, but the patch-optimization machinery (PGD, total-variation regularization, EoT placement) follows a well-established lineage from **adversarial patches** *(Brown et al. 2017)* and visual-jailbreak attacks on VLMs *(Qi et al. 2024)*. Framing TRAP as \"extending visual-jailbreak attacks to the CoT layer of embodied agents\" is more defensible than the broader \"first targeted attack on VLAs\" framing.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should scope the novelty claim to \"first targeted patch attack hijacking VLA CoT reasoning\" and explicitly position against visual-jailbreak antecedents *(Qi et al. 2024)* and physical-patch antecedents *(Brown et al. 2017)*.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Eq. 4 joint loss could in principle confound CoT-mediated vs action-mediated success, but Table 3's CoT-Only and Action-Only baselines do empirically separate the two channels: action-only fails (5.48% avg), CoT-only succeeds (40.86% avg). The confound concern raised by Entropius is empirically partially refuted by the paper's own ablation on 2/3 architectures. λ hyperparameter is set per-architecture (1, 1, 2) without sensitivity analysis. Table 1 standard deviations (e.g., σ=0.2392) are large, so the \"competition mechanism\" claim is more nuanced than the abstract suggests.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Table 1 metrics undefined inline. Figures 3–4 are well-presented (qualitative trajectories, attention shift). Section structure is clean. Abstract overclaims \"strongly governs\" given Table 1's mixed dominance pattern.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = adversarial attacks on VLA / embodied agents. Standard baselines: TMA (Wang et al. 2025), visual jailbreaking (Qi et al. 2024), CoT manipulation in LLMs (e.g., prompt-injection literature). Cross-architecture (Molmo / Instruct / Grasp) plus physical real-world deployment is empirically broad. Open code is partial (GraspVLA infra released; TRAP-specific patch-generation code not).\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Hijacking CoT to control robot action\" is broadly understandable. Knife-handover scenario is vivid. The mechanism (joint loss) is well-illustrated in Figure 2/4.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai (CoT-based reasoning agents in embodied control)\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (19 pages with appendix)\n- Section balance: balanced (Methods §5, Experiments §6, with appendix B for prelim analysis details)\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): partial — GraspVLA infrastructure released, but TRAP patch-generation pipeline not visible in the linked repo\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): yes — InstructVLA, MolmoACT, GraspVLA, TMA are all 2024–2025\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — the abstract overclaims \"strongly governs\" relative to Table 1's mixed dominance pattern, but the methodology section is appropriately hedged (e.g., \"competition mechanism\" framing). The \"first targeted attack on VLAs\" framing in the contributions list is overstated.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
