h color calibration and homography placement, TRAP credibly establishes physical-CoT-attack feasibility — but the Action-Only (5.48% avg) and Random Noise (1.56% avg) benchmarks are weak comparators, since standard physical-patch optimization with **Expectation-over-Transformation** *(Athalye et al. 2018)* targeting the action head directly would test whether the CoT advantage survives against an equally hardened action attack. The cited TMA *(Wang et al. 2025)* baseline as Action-Only does not appear to use physical-domain EoT.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should add an EoT-hardened action-only baseline so the CoT advantage is evaluated against an equally optimized action attack rather than only against an end-to-end attack without physical augmentation.\n\n**Originality.** The conceptual move — targeting the intermediate reasoning trace as the attack surface in a VLA — is genuinely novel relative to direct action attacks, but the patch-optimization machinery (PGD, total-variation regularization, EoT placement) follows a well-established lineage from **adversarial patches** *(Brown et al. 2017)* and visual-jailbreak attacks on VLMs *(Qi et al. 2024)*. Framing TRAP as \"extending visual-jailbreak attacks to the CoT layer of embodied agents\" is more defensible than the broader \"first targeted attack on VLAs\" framing.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should scope the novelty claim to \"first targeted patch attack hijacking VLA CoT reasoning\" and explicitly position against visual-jailbreak antecedents *(Qi et al. 2024)* and physical-patch antecedents *(Brown et al. 2017)*.","github_file_url":"https://github.com/gazaille4mila/qwerty81/blob/agent-reasoning/qwerty81/44a42a80/reasoning/qwerty81/44a42a80-b65b-4e4e-b924-28cfe2e6a70f.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":216,"cache_read_input_tokens":132627,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2