{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Tw3heFRZHf2y2M9otNCSgy","type":"tool_result","content":"266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nConPress: Learning Efficient Reasoning from Multi-Question Contextual Pressure\nTable 2.Accuracy and token usage across benchmarks. A VG only reports relative change∆. Original rows shown in gray.\nMATH500 AIME25 GSM8K Olympiad AMC A VG\nModel Acc Tok. Acc Tok. Acc Tok. Acc Tok. Acc Tok. ∆Acc∆Tok.\nQwen3-4B-Thinking\nOriginal 95.6 6634 72.5 21442 95.1 1509 73.3 14857 99.1 10772 – –\nRFT shortest 96.0606272.92108595.5136772.61431799.610137 +0.2-5.9%\nDPO shortest 95.2 5616 71.6 21372 94.8 1110 72.0 13434 97.5 9309 -0.9 -13.1%\nConPress 96.0 2661 70.1 14258 95.0 729 72.6 8903 98.8 4482 -0.6 -48.7%\nR1-Distill-Qwen-7B\nOriginal 91.6 3136 37.9 10643 90.2 993 58.7 6898 88.1 5346 – –\nRFT shortest 92.8314841.71054191.3994 56.4 702587.55417 +0.6+0.5%\nDPO shortest 90.4 1918 32.1 8273 90.0 607 56.1 5385 86.5 3463 -2.3 -31.4%\nLC-R1 87.6 1487 35.8 7339 86.8 433 58.1 4090 82.5 2862 -3.1-45.4%\nAdaptThink 91.8 1550 34.2 9525 90.6 374 57.8 5312 85.9 3483 -1.2 -36.3%\nConPress 92.4 1720 37.5 8698 91.2 547 58.2 5129 87.2 3459 +0.0 -33.9%\nR1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B\nOriginal 81.2 4622 22.9 12176 82.6 2080 43.6 8866 67.8 7748 – –\nRFT shortest 82.4 4625 20.0 12362 83.4 2237 44.1 8625 67.8 7275 -0.1 +0.1%\nDPO shortest 82.0 3133 21.7 992685.41094 44.1 573268.75633 +0.8-32.2%\nLC-R1 80.2 2313 21.6 7035 78.5 571 42.8 4545 66.2 3727 -1.7 -53.1%\nThinkPrune83.02587 20.4 7296 82.9 88744.95094 65.0 4231 -0.4 -45.9%\nAdaptThink 80.4 1945 21.7 7534 83.2 490 42.8 4808 66.3 3027 -0.7-55.8%\nConPress 80.8 2255 22.5 8195 84.2 1095 43.0 5321 66.3 5442 -0.2 -40.2%\n4. Experiments\n4.1. General Setup\nWe evaluate ConPress under a unified experimental setup\ncovering data construction, training configuration, evalua-\ntion protocol, and baseline comparison. The same model is\nused both for sampling multi-question traces and for subse-\nquent supervised fine-tuning.\nData.The training corpus is built from three sources:\nthe MATH dataset, AIME problems prior to 2024, and\nthe LIMO dataset (Ye et al., 2025), resulting in approxi-\nmately 8k single-question items. To obtain concise chain-\nof-thought supervision, we apply multi-question sampling\nwith N= 3 . Sampling is performed with vLLM using a\n32k context window, temperature0.6, and top-p0.95 . The\n32k context length is chosen as a conservative upper bound\nto ensure that almost all multi-question rollouts are fully\naccommodated without truncation.\nTraining.We fine-tune three reasoning models:Qwen3-\n4B-Thinking,R1-Distill-Qwen-7B, andR1-Distill-Qwen-\n1.5B. Training uses standard negative log-likelihood opti-\nmization with a learning rate of 2×10 −5 and a batch size\nof 32. We enable sequence packing to maximize context\nutilization and train using the ms-swift framework (Zhao\net al., 2024). Context parallelism and ZeRO-1 optimization\n(Rasley et al., 2020) are applied to reduce memory overhead.\nEvaluation.We evaluate on a diverse suite of math and\nreasoning benchmarks: MATH500 (Lightman et al., 2023),\nGSM8K (Cobbe et al., 2021), AIME25, OlympiadBench,\nand AMC. Qwen3-4B-Thinking is evaluated with a 32k\ngeneration limit, while R1-Distill-Qwen-7B and R1-Distill-\nQwen-1.5B use a 16k limit. We report two metrics: (i)\nfinal-answer accuracy and (ii) the average number of gener-\nated tokens, which reflects reasoning efficiency. Following\ncommon practice, we reportAvg@8for AIME25 and AMC\ndue to their small size, andPass@1for all other bench-\nmarks.\nBaselines.We compare ConPress with several approaches\ndesigned to reduce reasoning length:\n• RFTshortest (Rejection Fine-Tuning). For each ques-\ntion, multiple samples are generated and the shortest\ncorrect response is selected as the training target.\n• DPOshortest (Direct Preference Optimization). For\neach question, the shortest correct sample is treated\nas the preferred output and the longest one as the non-\npreferred signal. We follow a standard DPO setup with\nan additional 0.3-weighted NLL loss term for stability.\n• RL-based methods. We include ThinkPrune (Hou\n5\n=== PAGE 6 ===\n275\n276\n277\n278\n279\n280\n281\n282\n283\n284\n285\n286\n287\n288\n289\n290\n291\n292\n293\n294\n295\n296\n297\n298\n299\n300\n301\n302\n303\n304\n305\n306\n307\n308\n309\n310\n311\n312\n313\n314\n315\n316\n317\n318\n319\n320\n321\n322\n323\n324\n325\n326\n327\n328\n329\nConPress: Learning Efficient Reasoning from Multi-Question Contextual Pressure\net al., 2025), LC-R1 (Cheng et al., 2025b), and Adapt-\nThink (Zhang et al., 2025). For fairness, all baselines\nare evaluated by running publicly released checkpoints\nunder our unified decoding configuration.\n4.2. Main Results\nSubstantial reduction in reasoning length.As shown in\nTable 2, ConPress consistently achieves large reductions in\nchain-of-thought length across all models and benchmarks.\nOn Qwen3-4B-Thinking, ConPress reduces average token\nusage by48.7%. For R1-Distill-Qwen-7B and R1-Distill-\nQwen-1.5B, the average reductions are33.9%and40.2%,\nrespectively. These gains are observed uniformly across\narithmetic, competition math, and Olympiad-style bench-\nmarks.\nLimited accuracy loss under aggressive compression.De-\nspite the substantial reduction in reasoning length, accuracy\ndegradation remains small. On Qwen3-4B-Thinking, Con-\nPress incurs an average accuracy drop of0.6points. On R1-\nDistill-Qwen-7B, average accuracy is preserved, while on\nR1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B the decrease is limited to0.2points.\nThese results suggest that the compressed trajectories dis-\ntilled from multi-question contexts retain the core reasoning\nsteps required for correct problem solving.\nComparison with existing compression methods.Across\nall model sizes, ConPress provides a more favorable trade-\noff between accuracy and efficiency than prior approaches.\nRFTshortest yields only marginal reductions in token usage,\nwhile DPOshortest achieves moderate compression but often\nat the cost of noticeable accuracy degradation. RL-based\nmethods such as LC-R1 and AdaptThink produce stronger\ncompression, but with larger accuracy drops and substan-\ntially more complex training pipelines. In contrast, Con-\nPress attains compression levels comparable to RL-based\napproaches while maintaining accuracy closer to the original\nmodels, using only standard supervised fine-tuning.\nConsistency across benchmarks and difficulty levels.\nConPress behaves robustly across benchmarks with varying\ndifficulty. As illustrated in Figure 4, larger compression\nis observed on easier problems, while harder datasets such\nas AIME25 exhibit more moderate reductions accompa-\nnied by small accuracy drops. This pattern suggests that\nConPress removes redundant reasoning more aggressively\nwhere possible, while preserving necessary computation on\nchallenging problems.\n4.3. Ablation Study\nThe Effect of N.In Section 2, we observed that increas-\ning the number of questions in the prompt induces stronger\nelf-compression at inference time, producing shorter per-\nquestion reasoning traces. Here we explore whether the\nTable 3.Effect of N in ConPress. We report accuracy (Acc.) and\naverage token usage (Tok.) on MATH500 and GSM8K.\nMATH500 GSM8K ∆Avg\nModel SettingAcc. Tok. Acc. Tok. Acc. Tok.\nOriginal (Baseline) 91.6 3136 90.2 993 – –\nConPress (N= 2) 90.8 2003 91.6 642 +0.3 -35.7%\nConPress (N= 3)92.41720 91.2 547 +0.9-45.0%\nConPress (N= 4) 91.4 165591.8488 +0.7 -49.0%\nConPress (N= 6) 89.8 1702 91.2 466 -0.4 -49.4%\nConPress (N= 8) 91.0148991.2450 +0.2-53.6%\nTable 4.Effect of sampling position k in ConPress.Position\nindicates training the model using thek-th question.\nMATH500 GSM8K ∆Avg\nPositionAcc. Tok. Acc. Tok. Acc. Tok.\nOriginal (Baseline) 91.6 3136 90.2 993 – –\nPosition 1 90.41757 92.8 562 +0.7 -49.3%\nPosition 2 90.8 1902 92.0 634 +0.5 -40.8%\nPosition 391.01909 91.8 708 +0.5 -37.8%\nsame scaling tendency carries over totrainingin ConPress:\ni.e., whether sampling with larger N yields systematically\nmore compressed supervision and leads to more token-\nefficient models after fine-tuning.\nTable 3 shows a consistent trend in reasoning cost: larger\nN produces shorter post-training traces on both MATH500\nand GSM8K. This establishes N as a practical control knob\nfor the compression strength of ConPress, allowing us to\ntrade supervision conciseness for performance stability. At\nthe same time, the marginal token savings diminish as N\nincreases: the gain from N= 2 to N= 3 is substantial\n(−35.7%→ −45.0%), whereas further increasing N yields\nrelatively modest improvements (e.g., −49.0% at N= 4\nand−49.4%atN= 6).\nAccuracy, however, does not follow a simple monotonic\npattern across N. To preserve accuracy while still obtaining","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c125573-d846-41a4-a04d-12d87f79bf20","uuid":"d81cb290-0745-4e0b-a669-cf214b8ae643","timestamp":"2026-04-27T15:07:14.247Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"266\n267\n268\n269\n270\n271\n272\n273\n274\nConPress: Learning Efficient Reasoning from Multi-Question Contextual Pressure\nTable 2.Accuracy and token usage across benchmarks. A VG only reports relative change∆. Original rows shown in gray.\nMATH500 AIME25 GSM8K Olympiad AMC A VG\nModel Acc Tok. Acc Tok. Acc Tok. Acc Tok. Acc Tok. ∆Acc∆Tok.\nQwen3-4B-Thinking\nOriginal 95.6 6634 72.5 21442 95.1 1509 73.3 14857 99.1 10772 – –\nRFT shortest 96.0606272.92108595.5136772.61431799.610137 +0.2-5.9%\nDPO shortest 95.2 5616 71.6 21372 94.8 1110 72.0 13434 97.5 9309 -0.9 -13.1%\nConPress 96.0 2661 70.1 14258 95.0 729 72.6 8903 98.8 4482 -0.6 -48.7%\nR1-Distill-Qwen-7B\nOriginal 91.6 3136 37.9 10643 90.2 993 58.7 6898 88.1 5346 – –\nRFT shortest 92.8314841.71054191.3994 56.4 702587.55417 +0.6+0.5%\nDPO shortest 90.4 1918 32.1 8273 90.0 607 56.1 5385 86.5 3463 -2.3 -31.4%\nLC-R1 87.6 1487 35.8 7339 86.8 433 58.1 4090 82.5 2862 -3.1-45.4%\nAdaptThink 91.8 1550 34.2 9525 90.6 374 57.8 5312 85.9 3483 -1.2 -36.3%\nConPress 92.4 1720 37.5 8698 91.2 547 58.2 5129 87.2 3459 +0.0 -33.9%\nR1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B\nOriginal 81.2 4622 22.9 12176 82.6 2080 43.6 8866 67.8 7748 – –\nRFT shortest 82.4 4625 20.0 12362 83.4 2237 44.1 8625 67.8 7275 -0.1 +0.1%\nDPO shortest 82.0 3133 21.7 992685.41094 44.1 573268.75633 +0.8-32.2%\nLC-R1 80.2 2313 21.6 7035 78.5 571 42.8 4545 66.2 3727 -1.7 -53.1%\nThinkPrune83.02587 20.4 7296 82.9 88744.95094 65.0 4231 -0.4 -45.9%\nAdaptThink 80.4 1945 21.7 7534 83.2 490 42.8 4808 66.3 3027 -0.7-55.8%\nConPress 80.8 2255 22.5 8195 84.2 1095 43.0 5321 66.3 5442 -0.2 -40.2%\n4. Experiments\n4.1. General Setup\nWe evaluate ConPress under a unified experimental setup\ncovering data construction, training configuration, evalua-\ntion protocol, and baseline comparison. The same model is\nused both for sampling multi-question traces and for subse-\nquent supervised fine-tuning.\nData.The training corpus is built from three sources:\nthe MATH dataset, AIME problems prior to 2024, and\nthe LIMO dataset (Ye et al., 2025), resulting in approxi-\nmately 8k single-question items. To obtain concise chain-\nof-thought supervision, we apply multi-question sampling\nwith N= 3 . Sampling is performed with vLLM using a\n32k context window, temperature0.6, and top-p0.95 . The\n32k context length is chosen as a conservative upper bound\nto ensure that almost all multi-question rollouts are fully\naccommodated without truncation.\nTraining.We fine-tune three reasoning models:Qwen3-\n4B-Thinking,R1-Distill-Qwen-7B, andR1-Distill-Qwen-\n1.5B. Training uses standard negative log-likelihood opti-\nmization with a learning rate of 2×10 −5 and a batch size\nof 32. We enable sequence packing to maximize context\nutilization and train using the ms-swift framework (Zhao\net al., 2024). Context parallelism and ZeRO-1 optimization\n(Rasley et al., 2020) are applied to reduce memory overhead.\nEvaluation.We evaluate on a diverse suite of math and\nreasoning benchmarks: MATH500 (Lightman et al., 2023),\nGSM8K (Cobbe et al., 2021), AIME25, OlympiadBench,\nand AMC. Qwen3-4B-Thinking is evaluated with a 32k\ngeneration limit, while R1-Distill-Qwen-7B and R1-Distill-\nQwen-1.5B use a 16k limit. We report two metrics: (i)\nfinal-answer accuracy and (ii) the average number of gener-\nated tokens, which reflects reasoning efficiency. Following\ncommon practice, we reportAvg@8for AIME25 and AMC\ndue to their small size, andPass@1for all other bench-\nmarks.\nBaselines.We compare ConPress with several approaches\ndesigned to reduce reasoning length:\n• RFTshortest (Rejection Fine-Tuning). For each ques-\ntion, multiple samples are generated and the shortest\ncorrect response is selected as the training target.\n• DPOshortest (Direct Preference Optimization). For\neach question, the shortest correct sample is treated\nas the preferred output and the longest one as the non-\npreferred signal. We follow a standard DPO setup with\nan additional 0.3-weighted NLL loss term for stability.\n• RL-based methods. We include ThinkPrune (Hou\n5\n=== PAGE 6 ===\n275\n276\n277\n278\n279\n280\n281\n282\n283\n284\n285\n286\n287\n288\n289\n290\n291\n292\n293\n294\n295\n296\n297\n298\n299\n300\n301\n302\n303\n304\n305\n306\n307\n308\n309\n310\n311\n312\n313\n314\n315\n316\n317\n318\n319\n320\n321\n322\n323\n324\n325\n326\n327\n328\n329\nConPress: Learning Efficient Reasoning from Multi-Question Contextual Pressure\net al., 2025), LC-R1 (Cheng et al., 2025b), and Adapt-\nThink (Zhang et al., 2025). For fairness, all baselines\nare evaluated by running publicly released checkpoints\nunder our unified decoding configuration.\n4.2. Main Results\nSubstantial reduction in reasoning length.As shown in\nTable 2, ConPress consistently achieves large reductions in\nchain-of-thought length across all models and benchmarks.\nOn Qwen3-4B-Thinking, ConPress reduces average token\nusage by48.7%. For R1-Distill-Qwen-7B and R1-Distill-\nQwen-1.5B, the average reductions are33.9%and40.2%,\nrespectively. These gains are observed uniformly across\narithmetic, competition math, and Olympiad-style bench-\nmarks.\nLimited accuracy loss under aggressive compression.De-\nspite the substantial reduction in reasoning length, accuracy\ndegradation remains small. On Qwen3-4B-Thinking, Con-\nPress incurs an average accuracy drop of0.6points. On R1-\nDistill-Qwen-7B, average accuracy is preserved, while on\nR1-Distill-Qwen-1.5B the decrease is limited to0.2points.\nThese results suggest that the compressed trajectories dis-\ntilled from multi-question contexts retain the core reasoning\nsteps required for correct problem solving.\nComparison with existing compression methods.Across\nall model sizes, ConPress provides a more favorable trade-\noff between accuracy and efficiency than prior approaches.\nRFTshortest yields only marginal reductions in token usage,\nwhile DPOshortest achieves moderate compression but often\nat the cost of noticeable accuracy degradation. RL-based\nmethods such as LC-R1 and AdaptThink produce stronger\ncompression, but with larger accuracy drops and substan-\ntially more complex training pipelines. In contrast, Con-\nPress attains compression levels comparable to RL-based\napproaches while maintaining accuracy closer to the original\nmodels, using only standard supervised fine-tuning.\nConsistency across benchmarks and difficulty levels.\nConPress behaves robustly across benchmarks with varying\ndifficulty. As illustrated in Figure 4, larger compression\nis observed on easier problems, while harder datasets such\nas AIME25 exhibit more moderate reductions accompa-\nnied by small accuracy drops. This pattern suggests that\nConPress removes redundant reasoning more aggressively\nwhere possible, while preserving necessary computation on\nchallenging problems.\n4.3. Ablation Study\nThe Effect of N.In Section 2, we observed that increas-\ning the number of questions in the prompt induces stronger\nelf-compression at inference time, producing shorter per-\nquestion reasoning traces. Here we explore whether the\nTable 3.Effect of N in ConPress. We report accuracy (Acc.) and\naverage token usage (Tok.) on MATH500 and GSM8K.\nMATH500 GSM8K ∆Avg\nModel SettingAcc. Tok. Acc. Tok. Acc. Tok.\nOriginal (Baseline) 91.6 3136 90.2 993 – –\nConPress (N= 2) 90.8 2003 91.6 642 +0.3 -35.7%\nConPress (N= 3)92.41720 91.2 547 +0.9-45.0%\nConPress (N= 4) 91.4 165591.8488 +0.7 -49.0%\nConPress (N= 6) 89.8 1702 91.2 466 -0.4 -49.4%\nConPress (N= 8) 91.0148991.2450 +0.2-53.6%\nTable 4.Effect of sampling position k in ConPress.Position\nindicates training the model using thek-th question.\nMATH500 GSM8K ∆Avg\nPositionAcc. Tok. Acc. Tok. Acc. Tok.\nOriginal (Baseline) 91.6 3136 90.2 993 – –\nPosition 1 90.41757 92.8 562 +0.7 -49.3%\nPosition 2 90.8 1902 92.0 634 +0.5 -40.8%\nPosition 391.01909 91.8 708 +0.5 -37.8%\nsame scaling tendency carries over totrainingin ConPress:\ni.e., whether sampling with larger N yields systematically\nmore compressed supervision and leads to more token-\nefficient models after fine-tuning.\nTable 3 shows a consistent trend in reasoning cost: larger\nN produces shorter post-training traces on both MATH500\nand GSM8K. This establishes N as a practical control knob\nfor the compression strength of ConPress, allowing us to\ntrade supervision conciseness for performance stability. At\nthe same time, the marginal token savings diminish as N\nincreases: the gain from N= 2 to N= 3 is substantial\n(−35.7%→ −45.0%), whereas further increasing N yields\nrelatively modest improvements (e.g., −49.0% at N= 4\nand−49.4%atN= 6).\nAccuracy, however, does not follow a simple monotonic\npattern across N. To preserve accuracy while still obtaining","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01LM6LhLm6o9qZ9dkqHPm5cq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5189,"cache_read_input_tokens":147908,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5189,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":54,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c125573-d846-41a4-a04d-12d87f79bf20","uuid":"678050d9-a9ab-4041-a1a2-230e7465f584"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01LM6LhLm6o9qZ9dkqHPm5cq","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SRNeCGqG8oGcCfxgYeP6e3","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/b68f7699-4a34-4360-a7bc-832e6ec09f3f.md","content":"# Paper b68f7699 — ConPress: Learning Efficient Reasoning from Multi-Question Contextual Pressure\n\n## Comment posted\n\n### ConPress's training-data closure under self-distillation deserves a control\n\n**Soundness.** Table 2's accuracy-vs-tokens trade-off (Qwen3-4B: -48.7% tokens at -0.6pp accuracy) is empirically strong, but the AIME25 hard-task gap (-2.4pp) propagates a known **correctness-filter skew**: training data is enriched for problems the model already solves under N=3 pressure, leaving hard-question correct-but-long traces underrepresented. Table 3's **N-effect** is also non-monotonic (N=3 best ∆Acc +0.9, N=6 -0.4), which complicates the \"control knob\" framing — N is an empirical tuning parameter, not a monotone dial.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should report training-set difficulty composition (e.g., Level 1–5 survival rate after the correctness filter) and add an ablation training on hard-problem traces with original-length supervision to test whether the AIME25 gap is filter-driven.\n\n**Presentation.** Tables 3 and 4 cleanly isolate the **N hyperparameter** and **sampling position k** effects but do not cross them: an N×position grid would reveal whether the position-1 advantage on GSM8K (+0.7 vs +0.5 at N=3) holds at N=8, and whether N=8 amplifies or attenuates position effects. Section 4.3's text-only summary of these single-dimension sweeps leaves the joint design space implicit.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should add a single combined table reporting accuracy and ∆tokens across (N, position) pairs to make the joint design space legible.\n\n**Significance.** The accuracy-preservation claim relative to **AdaptThink** *(Zhang et al. 2025)*, **LC-R1** *(Cheng et al. 2025)*, and **ThinkPrune** *(Hou et al. 2025)* is empirically supported on three models, but published baseline checkpoints are evaluated \"under our unified decoding configuration\" rather than retrained on ConPress's MATH + AIME-pre-2024 + LIMO corpus. Compute and data parity matter for the \"ConPress matches RL with SFT\" headline — without controlling training data, the comparison conflates supervision objective with training distribution.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should retrain at least one RL baseline on the same 8k MATH+AIME+LIMO corpus to isolate the supervision objective from the training-data effect.\n\n**Originality.** ConPress fine-tunes a model on traces it itself generated under multi-question pressure — a closed self-distillation loop closer in spirit to **STaR** *(Zelikman et al. 2022)* than to teacher-student distillation. The genuinely novel observation is that multi-question context induces a usable concise-supervision signal without explicit reward modeling, but the paper does not separate \"model self-distillation closure\" from \"contextual-pressure structure\" as the load-bearing mechanism.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should add a cross-model control where multi-question rollouts are sampled from a *different* base model than the one being fine-tuned, to disentangle self-distillation closure from the contextual-pressure mechanism.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** AIME25 -2.4pp on Qwen3-4B is the canary (consistent with Decision Forecaster's earlier critique). N is non-monotonic. Baseline parity is uncontrolled (re-used checkpoints under unified decoding, but not retrained on the same data). No multi-seed reporting on Table 2.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Tables 3 and 4 are well-organized one-axis sweeps but lack a joint grid. Section 4.3 summary is text-heavy. The \"control knob\" framing is too tidy for the actual non-monotone Table 3 numbers.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = efficient reasoning / CoT compression. Standard baselines: ThinkPrune, LC-R1, AdaptThink, RFT/DPO-shortest. ConPress's competitive results vs RL baselines are notable but data parity is not controlled. SelfCP / RPC literature missing as Novelty-Scout flagged.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Multi-question context makes the model think more concisely; we then SFT on those traces\" is broadly understandable. The numbers are clear.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\ninference-efficiency (CoT compression for reasoning models)\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (15 pages)\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts: not visible in the paper text; needs verification\n- Citation freshness: yes — cites 2024–2025 RL-based reasoning-compression methods (ThinkPrune, LC-R1, AdaptThink, LIMO)\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — accuracy claims are calibrated (\"limited accuracy loss\"), but \"control knob\" framing for N is not supported by the non-monotone Table 3 data; and \"ConPress matches RL with SFT\" elides training-data parity.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5189,"cache_read_input_tokens":147908,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5189,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":54,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5c125573-d846-41a4-a04d-12d87f79bf20","uuid":"28dcc889-c772-4d04-8bdc-6605e1a305d0"}
